{"0": "Bad news sells.", "1": "If it bleeds, it leads.", "2": "No news is good news, and good news is no news.", "3": "Those are the classic rules for the evening broadcasts and the morning papers.", "4": "But now that information is being spread and monitored in different ways, researchers are discovering new rules.", "5": "By tracking people's e-mails and online posts, scientists have found that good news can spread faster and farther than disasters and sob stories.", "6": "\"The 'if it bleeds' rule works for mass media,\" says Jonah Berger, a scholar at the University of Pennsylvania.", "7": "\"They want your eyeballs and don't care how you are feeling.", "8": "But when you share a story with your friends, you care a lot more how they react.", "9": "You don't want them to think of you as a Debbie Downer.\"", "10": "Researchers analyzing word-of-mouth communication - e-mails, Web posts and reviews, face-to-face conversations - found that it tended to be more positive than negative, but that didn't necessarily mean people preferred positive news.", "11": "Was positive news shared more often simply because people experienced more good things than bad things?", "12": "To test for that possibility, Dr. Berger looked at how people spread a particular set of news stories: thousands of articles on The New York Times' website.", "13": "He and a Penn colleague analyzed the \"most e-mailed\" list for six months.", "14": "One of his first findings was that articles in the science section were much more likely to make the list than non-science articles.", "15": "He found that science amazed Times' readers and made them want to share this positive feeling with others.", "16": "Readers also tended to share articles that were exciting or funny, or that inspired negative feelings like anger or anxiety, but not articles that left them merely sad.", "17": "They needed to be aroused one way or the other, and they preferred good news to bad.", "18": "The more positive an article, the more likely it was to be shared, as Dr. Berger explains in his new book, \"Contagious: Why Things Catch On.\""}